 the economic conflict that provided a major impetus for the resistance that culminated in the Revolution of 1952-the most important revolutionary event in Latin America since the Mexican Revolution of 1910. The emergence of another revolutionary movement in Bolivia early in the millennium under Evo Morales makes this study of its Cold War predecessor an illuminating and timely exploration of the recurrent tensions between U.S. efforts to establish and dominate a liberal capitalist world order and the counterefforts of Latin American countries like Bolivia to forge their own destinies in the shadow of the "colossus of the north."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aTin industryxGovernment policyxHistoryx20th centuryxBolivia. 0aTin industryxGovernment policyzBoliviaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTinxPricesxHistoryx20th centuryxBolivia. 0aTinxPriceszBoliviaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271056869zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056869.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK